...a lowest possible value of 375 ETH (12.5 ETH x 30) or $992,516.25. A $300,000 profit. Higher floor price obviously increases his profit margins significantly.

So, what do we learn?

1. NFT trading is inherently and obviously high-risk.

If the floor trends downward, Flur is looking at serious loss. Imagine 3-5 ETH, which would equate to somewhere around $350,000 loss.

However, the upside risk is obviously phenomenal. If IF matched #Doodles in some reasonably quick timeframe, Flur's bag would have..

If price did trend downward, Flur may need to exit strategically (without tanking the market). However, we all know that this is difficult when competing with motivated buyers. 

Ultimately, Flur operates at a different level to most people, but parallels can be drawn.

2. Offload the more aesthetically valuable/rarer IFs at higher prices to offset the current deficit.

A more difficult position for Flur would be if the price discovery trends downward. Flur may have an exit strategy in place, a stop-loss of sorts.

1) Trying to bag a rare (which was a stated aim of Flur).

2) Having long-term belief in the project (Flur does).

3) Trading pre-reveal/post-reveal volatility (which Flur has not done - traded none so far).

At current 6.75 ETH floor Flur has a bag with a lowest possible value of 202.50 ETH ($533,994.53), which if realised would be a 61.03 ETH ($161,530.04) loss.
